02765 /**
02766  * cvmx_gser#_br_rx#_ctl
02767  */
02768 union cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl {
02769     uint64_t u64;
02770     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl_s {
02771 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02772     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
02773     uint64_t rxt_adtmout_disable          : 1;  /**< For BASE-R links the terminating condition for link training receiver adaptation
02774                                                          is a 330 milliseconds time-out timer.  When the receiver adaptation time-out timer
02775                                                          expires the receiver adaptation process is concluded and the link is considered good.
02776                                                          Note that when BASE-R link training is performed under software control,
02777                                                          (GSER()_BR_RX()_CTL[RXT_SWM] is set), the receiver adaptation time-out timer is disabled
02778                                                          and not used.
02779                                                          Set this bit to a one to disable the link training receiver adaptation time-out
02780                                                          timer during BASE-R link training under hardware control.  For diagnostic use only. */
02781     uint64_t rxt_swm                      : 1;  /**< Set when RX BASE-R link training is to be performed under software control.
02782                                                          See GSER()_BR_RX()_EER[EXT_EER]. */
02783     uint64_t rxt_preset                   : 1;  /**< For all link training, this bit determines how to configure the preset bit in the
02784                                                          coefficient update message that is sent to the far end transmitter. When set, a one time
02785                                                          request is made that the coefficients be set to a state where equalization is turned off.
02786                                                          To perform a preset, set this bit prior to link training. Link training needs to be
02787                                                          disabled to complete the request and get the rxtrain state machine back to idle. Note that
02788                                                          it is illegal to set both the preset and initialize bits at the same time. For diagnostic
02789                                                          use only. */
02790     uint64_t rxt_initialize               : 1;  /**< For all link training, this bit determines how to configure the initialize bit in the
02791                                                          coefficient update message that is sent to the far end transmitter of RX training. When
02792                                                          set, a request is made that the coefficients be set to its INITIALIZE state. To perform an
02793                                                          initialize prior to link training, set this bit prior to performing link training. Note
02794                                                          that it is illegal to set both the preset and initialize bits at the same time. Since the
02795                                                          far end transmitter is required to be initialized prior to starting link training, it is
02796                                                          not expected that software will need to set this bit. For diagnostic use only. */
02797 #else
02798     uint64_t rxt_initialize               : 1;
02799     uint64_t rxt_preset                   : 1;
02800     uint64_t rxt_swm                      : 1;
02801     uint64_t rxt_adtmout_disable          : 1;
02802     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
02803 #endif
02804     } s;
02805     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl_s        cn73xx;
02806     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl_s        cn78xx;
02807     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl_cn78xxp1 {
02808 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02809     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
02810     uint64_t rxt_swm                      : 1;  /**< Set when RX BASE-R link training is to be performed under software control.
02811                                                          See GSER()_BR_RX()_EER[EXT_EER]. */
02812     uint64_t rxt_preset                   : 1;  /**< For all link training, this bit determines how to configure the preset bit in the
02813                                                          coefficient update message that is sent to the far end transmitter. When set, a one time
02814                                                          request is made that the coefficients be set to a state where equalization is turned off.
02815                                                          To perform a preset, set this bit prior to link training. Link training needs to be
02816                                                          disabled to complete the request and get the rxtrain state machine back to idle. Note that
02817                                                          it is illegal to set both the preset and initialize bits at the same time. For diagnostic
02818                                                          use only. */
02819     uint64_t rxt_initialize               : 1;  /**< For all link training, this bit determines how to configure the initialize bit in the
02820                                                          coefficient update message that is sent to the far end transmitter of RX training. When
02821                                                          set, a request is made that the coefficients be set to its INITIALIZE state. To perform an
02822                                                          initialize prior to link training, set this bit prior to performing link training. Note
02823                                                          that it is illegal to set both the preset and initialize bits at the same time. Since the
02824                                                          far end transmitter is required to be initialized prior to starting link training, it is
02825                                                          not expected that software will need to set this bit. For diagnostic use only. */
02826 #else
02827     uint64_t rxt_initialize               : 1;
02828     uint64_t rxt_preset                   : 1;
02829     uint64_t rxt_swm                      : 1;
02830     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
02831 #endif
02832     } cn78xxp1;
02833     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl_s        cnf75xx;
02834 };
02835 typedef union cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_ctl_t;
02836 
02837 /**
02838  * cvmx_gser#_br_rx#_eer
02839  *
02840  * GSER software BASE-R RX link training equalization evaluation request (EER). A write to
02841  * [RXT_EER] initiates a equalization request to the RAW PCS. A read of this register returns the
02842  * equalization status message and a valid bit indicating it was updated. These registers are for
02843  * diagnostic use only.
02844  */
02845 union cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer {
02846     uint64_t u64;
02847     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer_s {
02848 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02849     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
02850     uint64_t rxt_eer                      : 1;  /**< When RX BASE-R link training is being performed under software control,
02851                                                          (GSER()_BR_RX()_CTL[RXT_SWM] is set), writing this bit initiates an equalization
02852                                                          request to the RAW PCS. Reading this bit always returns a zero.
02853                                                          When auto-negotiated link training is not present and link speed >= 5 Gbaud,
02854                                                          including XFI, receiver (only) equalization should be manually performed. After
02855                                                          GSER()_BR_RX()_CTL[RXT_SWM] is set, writing this CSR with
02856                                                          [RXT_EER]=1 initiates this manual equalization. The operation may take up to
02857                                                          2 milliseconds, and then hardware sets [RXT_ESV]. The SerDes input should
02858                                                          be a pattern (something similar to the BASE-R training sequence, ideally)
02859                                                          during this receiver-only training. If DFE is to be disabled
02860                                                          (recommended for 5 Gbaud and below), do it prior to this receiver-only
02861                                                          initialization. (GSER()_LANE()_RX_VALBBD_CTRL_0, GSER()_LANE()_RX_VALBBD_CTRL_1,
02862                                                          and GSER()_LANE()_RX_VALBBD_CTRL_2 configure the DFE.) */
02863     uint64_t rxt_esv                      : 1;  /**< When performing an equalization request (RXT_EER), this bit, when set, indicates that the
02864                                                          Equalization Status (RXT_ESM) is valid. When issuing a RXT_EER request, it is expected
02865                                                          that RXT_ESV will get written to zero so that a valid RXT_ESM can be determined. */
02866     uint64_t rxt_esm                      : 14; /**< When performing an equalization request (RXT_EER), this is the equalization status message
02867                                                          from the RAW PCS. It is valid when RXT_ESV is set.
02868                                                          _ <13:6>: Figure of merit. An 8-bit output from the PHY indicating the quality of the
02869                                                          received data eye. A higher value indicates better link equalization, with 8'd0 indicating
02870                                                          worst equalization setting and 8'd255 indicating the best equalization setting.
02871                                                          _ <5:4>: RX recommended TXPOST direction change.
02872                                                          _ <3:2>: RX recommended TXMAIN direction change.
02873                                                          _ <1:0>: RX recommended TXPRE direction change.
02874                                                          Recommended direction change outputs from the PHY for the link partner transmitter
02875                                                          coefficients.
02876                                                          0x0 = Hold.
02877                                                          0x1 = Increment.
02878                                                          0x2 = Decrement.
02879                                                          0x3 = Hold. */
02880 #else
02881     uint64_t rxt_esm                      : 14;
02882     uint64_t rxt_esv                      : 1;
02883     uint64_t rxt_eer                      : 1;
02884     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
02885 #endif
02886     } s;
02887     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer_s        cn73xx;
02888     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer_s        cn78xx;
02889     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer_s        cn78xxp1;
02890     struct cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer_s        cnf75xx;
02891 };
02892 typedef union cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer cvmx_gserx_br_rxx_eer_t;

02948  * equalizer taps (Pre/Swing/Post) are initialized with the values in this register.  Also,

03024                                                          the DLM are used in PIPE mode. [RMAC_PIPE] must only be set when [RMAC] is set. */

03029                                                          when any of [BGX,PCIE,RMAC] are set. [SRIO] must only be set for QLM2 and QLM3
03030                                                          (i.e. GSER2 and GSER3). */

03034     uint64_t bgx                          : 1;  /**< When set, indicates the GSER is configured for BGX mode. [BGX] must not be set

03036                                                          (i.e. GSER4 and GSER5). */

03039                                                          any of [BGX,SRIO,RMAC] are set. [PCIE] must only be set for DLM0 and DLM1
03040                                                          (i.e. GSER0 and GSER1). */

03047     uint64_t sata                         : 1;

03055 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

03057     uint64_t sata                         : 1;  /**< When set, indicates the GSER is configured for SATA mode. [SATA] must not be set
03058                                                          when either of [BGX,PCIE] are set. [SATA] must only be set for DLM4 (i.e. GSER4). */
03059     uint64_t bgx_quad                     : 1;  /**< When set, indicates the QLM is in BGX quad aggregation mode. [BGX_QUAD] must only be
03060                                                          set when [BGX] is set and [BGX_DUAL] is clear.
03061                                                          When [BGX_QUAD] is set, GSER bundles all four lanes for one BGX controller.
03062                                                          [BGX_QUAD] must only be set for the XAUI/DXAUI and XLAUI protocols.
03063                                                          [BGX_QUAD] must not be set in a DLM. */
03064     uint64_t bgx_dual                     : 1;  /**< When set, indicates the QLM is in BGX dual aggregation mode. [BGX_DUAL] must only be
03065                                                          set when [BGX] is also set and [BGX_QUAD] is clear.
03066                                                          When [BGX_DUAL] is set, GSER bundles lanes 0 and 1 for one BGX controller and bundles
03067                                                          lanes 2 and 3 for another BGX controller. [BGX_DUAL] must only be set for the RXAUI
03068                                                          protocol.
03069                                                          [BGX_DUAL] must not be set in a DLM. */

03075     uint64_t pcie                         : 1;  /**< Indicates the GSER is configured for PCIE mode. [PCIE] must not be set when
03076                                                          either of [SATA,BGX] are set. */
03077 #else
03078     uint64_t pcie                         : 1;
03079     uint64_t ila                          : 1;
03080     uint64_t bgx                          : 1;
03081     uint64_t bgx_dual                     : 1;
03082     uint64_t bgx_quad                     : 1;
03083     uint64_t sata                         : 1;
03084     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
03085 #endif
03086     } cn73xx;

03088 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

04306                                                          Set GSER()_GLBL_TM_ADMON[AMON_ON].
04307                                                          Decodes 0x0 - 0x4 require GSER()_GLBL_TM_ADMON[LSEL] set.
04308                                                          Decodes 0x5 - 0x5 do not require GSER()_GLBL_TM_ADMON[LSEL] set.

04310                                                          0x0 = TX txdrv DAC 100ua sink current monitor.

04315                                                          0x5 = Global bandgap voltage.
04316                                                          0x6 = Global CTAT voltage.
04317                                                          0x7 = Global internal 100ua reference current.
04318                                                          0x8 = Global external 100ua reference current.
04319                                                          0x9 = Global Rterm calibration reference voltage.
04320                                                          0xA = Global Rterm calibration comparator voltage.
04321                                                          0xB = Global force VCNT through DAC.
04322                                                          0xC = Global VDD voltage.
04323                                                          0xD = Global VDDCLK voltage.
04324                                                          0xE = Global PLL regulate VCO supply.
04325                                                          0xF = Global VCTRL for VCO varactor control. */

04327                                                          Set GSER()_GLBL_TM_ADMON[DMON_ON].

04329                                                          Decodes 0xf - 0x1f do not require GSER()_GLBL_TM_ADMON[LSEL] set.
04330                                                          In both cases, the resulting signals can be observed on the DMON pin.
04331                                                          0x00 = DFE Data Q.
04332                                                          0x01 = DFE Edge I.
04333                                                          0x02 = DFE CK Q.
04334                                                          0x03 = DFE CK I.
04335                                                          0x04 = DLL use GSER()_SLICE()_RX_SDLL_CTRL.PCS_SDS_RX_SDLL_SWSEL to select signal
04336                                                          in the slice DLL.
04337                                                          0x05-0x7 = Reserved.
04338                                                          0x08 = RX ld_rx[0].
04339                                                          0x09 = RX rx_clk.
04340                                                          0x0A = RX q_error_stg.
04341                                                          0x0B = RX q_data_stg.
04342                                                          0x0C-0x0E = Reserved.
04343                                                          0x0F = Special case to observe supply in global. Sds_vdda and a internal regulated supply
04344                                                          can be observed on DMON and DMONB
04345                                                          respectively.  sds_vss can be observed on AMON. GSER()_GLBL_TM_ADMON[AMON_ON]
04346                                                          must not be set.

04348                                                          0x11 = Sds_tst_fb_clk.
04349                                                          0x12 = Buffered refclk.
04350                                                          0x13 = Div 8 of core clock (core_clk_out).

05594                                                          are set.

05605                                                          5 Gbaud, pre-CTLE, post-CTLE, and peaking control settings should be manually

05607                                                          should both be set, [RX_SDS_RX_AGC_MVAL] has the pre and post settings,

05609                                                          peaking.

05611                                                          simulations with the IBIS-AMI model supplied by Cavium when
05612                                                          GSER()_LANE()_RX_CFG_5[RX_AGC_MEN_OVRRD_EN,RX_AGC_MEN_OVRRD_VAL] are set. */

05643                                                          GSER()_LANE()_RX_MISC_OVRRD[CFG_RS_ERRDET_CTRL_OVRRD_EN]
05644                                                          is set.
05645                                                          <15:13>: Starting delta (6.7mV/step, 13.4mV + 6.7mV*N).
05646                                                          <12:10>: Minimum delta to adapt to (6.7mV/step, 13.4mV + 6.7mV*N).
05647                                                          <9:7>: Window mode (PM) delta (6.7mV/step, 13.4mV + 6.7mV*N).
05648                                                          <6>: Enable DFE for edge samplers.
05649                                                          <5:4>: Edge sampler DEF alpha:
05650                                                          0x0 = 1/4.
05651                                                          0x1 = 1/2.
05652                                                          0x2 = 3/4.
05653                                                          0x3 = 1.
05654                                                          <3:0>: Q/QB error sampler 1 threshold, 6.7mV/step. */
05655 #else

05657     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
05658 #endif
05659     } s;

05759  * fields in these registers do not change during chip warm or soft resets.
05760  */

05783     uint64_t rx_ctle_pole_ovrrd_val       : 4;  /**< Equalizer pole adjustment override value.
05784                                                          RX precorrelation sample counter control
05785                                                          bit 3: Optimize CTLE during training.

05787                                                          bits 1:0:
05788                                                          0x0 = ~ 5dB of peaking at 4.0 GHz.
05789                                                          0x1 = ~10dB of peaking at 5.0 GHz.

05791                                                          0x3 = ~20dB of peaking at 6.0 GHz. */

05794     uint64_t pcs_sds_rx_ctle_pole_step    : 1;  /**< Step pole value (for VMA adaption, not applicable in manual mode). */
05795 #else
05796     uint64_t pcs_sds_rx_ctle_pole_step    : 1;
05797     uint64_t pcs_sds_rx_ctle_pole_min     : 2;

07147     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
07148     uint64_t lmode                        : 4;  /**< For links that are not in PCIE mode, used to index into the PHY
07149                                                          table to select electrical specs and link rate. Note that the PHY table can be modified
07150                                                          such that any supported link rate can be derived regardless of the configured LMODE.
07151                                                          0x0: R_25G_REFCLK100.
07152                                                          0x1: R_5G_REFCLK100.

07154                                                          0x3: R_125G_REFCLK15625_KX (not supported).

07156                                                          0x5: R_103125G_REFCLK15625_KR.
07157                                                          0x6: R_125G_REFCLK15625_SGMII.
07158                                                          0x7: R_5G_REFCLK15625_QSGMII (not supported).
07159                                                          0x8: R_625G_REFCLK15625_RXAUI (not supported).
07160                                                          0x9: R_25G_REFCLK125.
07161                                                          0xA: R_5G_REFCLK125.
07162                                                          0xB: R_8G_REFCLK125.
07163                                                          0xC - 0xF: Reserved.
07164                                                          This register is not used for PCIE configurations. This register
07165                                                          defaults to R_625G_REFCLK15625_RXAUI.
07166                                                          It is recommended that the PHY be in reset when reconfiguring the [LMODE]
07167                                                          (GSER()_PHY_CTL[PHY_RESET] is set).
07168                                                          Once the [LMODE] has been configured, and the PHY is out of reset, the table entries for
07169                                                          the
07170                                                          selected [LMODE] must be updated to reflect the reference clock speed. Refer to the
07171                                                          register
07172                                                          description and index into the table using the rate and reference speed to obtain the
07173                                                          recommended values.
07174                                                          _ Write GSER()_PLL_P()_MODE_0.
07175                                                          _ Write GSER()_PLL_P()_MODE_1.
07176                                                          _ Write GSER()_LANE_P()_MODE_0.
07177                                                          _ Write GSER()_LANE_P()_MODE_1.
07178                                                          where in "P(z)", z equals [LMODE]. */
07179 #else

07182 #endif

07791  */
07792 union cvmx_gserx_pcie_pipe_port_sel {

07798                                                           when in 4-Pipe Mode.
07799                                                           This bit should not be set in Single Pipe or 2-Pipe Mode.
07800                                                          - 0: PEM1 is tied to Pipe1/DLM1.  This is 3x1 PCIe mode when all 4 PIPES are enabled.

07805                                                              This is 1x4 PCIe mode.
07806                                                          - 10: 2-Pipe Mode.  Enables PIPEs 0 (PEM0) and 1 (PEM1).
07807                                                              This is 2x2 PCIe mode or 1x2 PCIe mode with SATA.
07808                                                          - 11: 4-Pipe Mode. Enables PIPEs 0 (PEM0), 1, 2 (PEM1), and 3 (PEM2).
07809                                                              This is 2x1 PCIe mode with SATA or 3x1 PCIe mode. */
07810 #else

07814 #endif

07832     uint64_t pipe3_rst                    : 1;  /**< Pipe 3 Reset.  Setting this bit will put Pipe 3 into reset.
07833                                                          PEM2 is always tied to Pipe 3. */
07834     uint64_t pipe2_rst                    : 1;  /**< Pipe 2 Reset.  Setting this bit will put Pipe 2 into reset.
07835                                                          PEM1 is tied to Pipe 2 in 3x1 PCIe mode (GSER_PCIE_PIPE_PORT_SEL.PIPE_PORT_SEL
07836                                                          is set to 4-pipe mode, and GSER_PCIE_PIPE_PORT_SEL.CFG_PEM1_DLM2 is also set). */
07837     uint64_t pipe1_rst                    : 1;  /**< Pipe 1 Reset.  Setting this bit will put Pipe 1 into reset.
07838                                                          PEM1 is tied to Pipe 1 in 2x2 PCIe or 2x1 PCIe with SATA modes. */
07839     uint64_t pipe0_rst                    : 1;  /**< Pipe 0 Reset.  Setting this bit will put Pipe 0 into reset.
07840                                                          PEM0 is always tied to Pipe 0. */
07841 #else
07842     uint64_t pipe0_rst                    : 1;
07843     uint64_t pipe1_rst                    : 1;
07844     uint64_t pipe2_rst                    : 1;
07845     uint64_t pipe3_rst                    : 1;
07846     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
07847 #endif
07848     } s;

07850     struct cvmx_gserx_pcie_pipe_rst_s     cn70xxp1;

08846 /**
08847  * cvmx_gser#_pll_p#_mode_0
08848  *
08849  * These are the RAW PCS PLL global settings mode 0 registers. There is one register per GSER per
08850  * GSER_LMODE_E value (0..11). Only one entry is used at any given time in a given GSER - the one
08851  * selected by the corresponding GSER()_LANE_MODE[LMODE].
08852  * These registers are reset by hardware only during chip cold reset.
08853  * The values of the CSR fields in these registers do not change during subsequent chip warm or
08854  * soft resets.
08855  */
08856 union cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_0 {
08857     uint64_t u64;
08858     struct cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_0_s {
08859 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08860     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
08861     uint64_t pll_icp                      : 4;  /**< PLL charge pump enable.
08862                                                          Recommended settings, which are based on the reference clock speed:
08863                                                          <pre>
08864                                                                   100MHz 125MHz 156.25MHz
08865                                                          1.25G:    0x1    0x1    0x1
08866                                                          2.5G:     0x4    0x3    0x3
08867                                                          3.125G:   NS     0x1    0x1
08868                                                          5.0G:     0x1    0x1    0x1
08869                                                          6.25G:    NS     0x1    0x1
08870                                                          8.0G:     0x3    0x2    NS
08871                                                          10.3125G: NS     NS     0x1
08872                                                          </pre>
08873                                                          For PCIE 1.1 X100MHz, [PLL_ICP] should be 4.
08874                                                          For PCIE 2.1 X100MHz, [PLL_ICP] should be 4.
08875                                                          For PCIE 1.1 X125MHz, [PLL_ICP] should be 3.
08876                                                          For PCIE 2.1 X125MHz, [PLL_ICP] should be 3.
08877                                                          A 'NS' indicates that the rate is not supported at the specified reference clock. */
08878     uint64_t pll_rloop                    : 3;  /**< Loop resistor tuning.
08879                                                          Recommended settings:
08880                                                          <pre>
08881                                                          _ 1.25G:    0x3
08882                                                          _ 2.5G:     0x3
08883                                                          _ 3.125G:   0x3
08884                                                          _ 5.0G:     0x3
08885                                                          _ 6.25G:    0x3
08886                                                          _ 8.0G:     0x5
08887                                                          _ 10.3125G: 0x5
08888                                                          </pre> */
08889     uint64_t pll_pcs_div                  : 9;  /**< The divider that generates PCS_MAC_TX_CLK. The frequency of the clock is (pll_frequency /
08890                                                          PLL_PCS_DIV).
08891                                                          Recommended settings:
08892                                                          <pre>
08893                                                                      PCIE   Other
08894                                                          _ 1.25G:     NS     0x28
08895                                                          _ 2.5G:      0x5    0x5
08896                                                          _ 3.125G:    NS     0x14
08897                                                          _ 5.0G:      0x5    0xA
08898                                                          _ 6.25G:     NS     0xA
08899                                                          _ 8.0G:      0x8    0xA
08900                                                          _ 10.3125G:  NS     0xA
08901                                                          </pre>
08902                                                          A 'NS' indicates that the rate is not supported at the specified reference clock. */
08903 #else
08904     uint64_t pll_pcs_div                  : 9;
08905     uint64_t pll_rloop                    : 3;
08906     uint64_t pll_icp                      : 4;
08907     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
08908 #endif
08909     } s;
08910     struct cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_0_s     cn73xx;
08911     struct cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_0_s     cn78xx;
08912     struct cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_0_s     cn78xxp1;
08913     struct cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_0_s     cnf75xx;
08914 };

08920  * These are the RAW PCS PLL global settings mode 1 registers. There is one register per GSER per

08922  * selected by the corresponding GSER()_LANE_MODE[LMODE].
08923  * These registers are reset by hardware only during chip cold reset.
08924  * The values of the CSR fields in this register do not change during subsequent chip warm or
08925  * soft resets.
08926  */
08927 union cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_1 {
08928     uint64_t u64;
08929     struct cvmx_gserx_pll_px_mode_1_s {
08930 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08931     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
08932     uint64_t pll_16p5en                   : 1;  /**< Enable for the DIV 16.5 divided down clock.
08933                                                          Recommended settings, based on the reference clock speed:
08934                                                          <pre>
08935                                                                   100MHz 125MHz 156.25MHz
08936                                                          1.25G:    0x1    0x1     0x1
08937                                                          2.5G:     0x0    0x0     0x0
08938                                                          3.125G:   NS     0x1     0x1
08939                                                          5.0G:     0x0    0x0     0x0
08940                                                          6.25G:    NS     0x0     0x0
08941                                                          8.0G:     0x0    0x0     NS
08942                                                          10.3125G: NS     NS      0x1
08943                                                          </pre>
08944                                                          A 'NS' indicates that the rate is not supported at the specified reference clock. */
08945     uint64_t pll_cpadj                    : 2;  /**< PLL charge adjust.
08946                                                          Recommended settings, based on the reference clock speed:
08947                                                          <pre>
08948                                                                    100MHz 125MHz 156.25MHz
08949                                                          1.25G:     0x2     0x2    0x3
08950                                                          2.5G:      0x2     0x1    0x2
08951                                                          3.125G:    NS      0x2    0x2
08952                                                          5.0G:      0x2     0x2    0x2
08953                                                          6.25G:     NS      0x2    0x2
08954                                                          8.0G:      0x2     0x1    NS
08955                                                          10.3125G:  NS      NS     0x2
08956                                                          </pre>
08957                                                          For PCIE 1.1 X100MHz, [PLL_CPADJ] should be 2.
08958                                                          For PCIE 2.1 X100MHz, [PLL_CPADJ] should be 2.
08959                                                          For PCIE 1.1 X125MHz, [PLL_CPADJ] should be 1.
08960                                                          For PCIE 2.1 X125MHz, [PLL_CPADJ] should be 1.
08961                                                          A 'NS' indicates that the rate is not supported at the specified reference clock. */
08962     uint64_t pll_pcie3en                  : 1;  /**< Enable PCIE3 mode.
08963                                                          Recommended settings:
08964                                                          0 = Any rate other than 8 Gbaud.
08965                                                          1 = Rate is equal to 8 Gbaud. */
08966     uint64_t pll_opr                      : 1;  /**< PLL op range:
08967                                                          0 = Use ring oscillator VCO. Recommended for rates 6.25 Gbaud and lower.
08968                                                          1 = Use LC-tank VCO. Recommended for rates 8 Gbaud and higher. */
08969     uint64_t pll_div                      : 9;  /**< PLL divider in feedback path which sets the PLL frequency.
08970                                                          Recommended settings:
08971                                                          <pre>
08972                                                                   100MHz 125MHz 156.25MHz
08973                                                          1.25G:    0x19   0x14    0x10
08974                                                          2.5G:     0x19   0x14    0x10
08975                                                          3.125G:   NS     0x19    0x14
08976                                                          5.0G:     0x19   0x14    0x10
08977                                                          6.25G:    NS     0x19    0x14
08978                                                          8.0G:     0x28   0x20    NS
08979                                                          10.3125G: NS     NS      0x21
08980                                                          </pre>
08981                                                          A 'NS' indicates that the rate is not supported at the specified reference clock. */
08982 #else

08986     uint64_t pll_cpadj                    : 2;
08987     uint64_t pll_16p5en                   : 1;

08989 #endif
08990     } s;

09227 union cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_detsts {
09228     uint64_t u64;
09229     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_detsts_s {
09230 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09231     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
09232     uint64_t cdrlock                      : 4;  /**< After an electrical idle exit condition (EIE) has been detected, the CDR needs 10000 UI to
09233                                                          lock. During this time, there may be RX bit errors. These bits will set when the CDR is
09234                                                          guaranteed to be locked. Note that link training can't start until the lane CDRLOCK is
09235                                                          set. Software can use CDRLOCK to determine when to expect error free RX data.
09236                                                          <11>: Lane 3.  Not supported in GSER0, GSER1, GSER4, GSER5, GSER6, GSER7, or GSER8.
09237                                                          <10>: Lane 2.  Not supported in GSER0, GSER1, GSER4, GSER5, GSER6, GSER7, or GSER8.
09238                                                          <9>: Lane 1.
09239                                                          <8>: Lane 0. */
09240     uint64_t eiests                       : 4;  /**< When electrical idle exit detection is enabled (GSER()_RX_EIE_DETEN[EIEDE] is
09241                                                          asserted), indicates that an electrical idle exit condition (EIE) was detected. For higher
09242                                                          data rates, the received data needs to have sufficient low frequency content (for example,
09243                                                          idle symbols) for data transitions to be detected and for [EIESTS] to stay set
09244                                                          accordingly.
09245                                                          Under most conditions, [EIESTS]
09246                                                          will stay asserted until GSER()_RX_EIE_DETEN[EIEDE] is deasserted.
09247                                                          <7>: Lane 3.  Not supported in GSER0, GSER1, GSER4, GSER5, GSER6, GSER7, or GSER8.
09248                                                          <6>: Lane 2.  Not supported in GSER0, GSER1, GSER4, GSER5, GSER6, GSER7, or GSER8.
09249                                                          <5>: Lane 1.
09250                                                          <4>: Lane 0. */
09251     uint64_t eieltch                      : 4;  /**< When electrical idle exit detection is enabled (GSER()_RX_EIE_DETEN[EIEDE] is
09252                                                          asserted), indicates that an electrical idle exit condition (EIE) was detected. Once an
09253                                                          EIE condition has been detected, the per-lane [EIELTCH] will stay set until
09254                                                          GSER()_RX_EIE_DETEN[EIEDE] is deasserted. Note that there may be RX bit errors until
09255                                                          CDRLOCK
09256                                                          is set.
09257                                                          <3>: Lane 3.  Not supported in GSER0, GSER1, GSER4, GSER5, GSER6, GSER7, or GSER8.
09258                                                          <2>: Lane 2.  Not supported in GSER0, GSER1, GSER4, GSER5, GSER6, GSER7, or GSER8.
09259                                                          <1>: Lane 1.
09260                                                          <0>: Lane 0. */
09261 #else
09262     uint64_t eieltch                      : 4;
09263     uint64_t eiests                       : 4;
09264     uint64_t cdrlock                      : 4;
09265     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
09266 #endif
09267     } s;
09268     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_detsts_s     cn73xx;

09275 /**
09276  * cvmx_gser#_rx_eie_filter
09277  */
09278 union cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter {
09279     uint64_t u64;
09280     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter_s {
09281 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09282     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
09283     uint64_t eii_filt                     : 16; /**< The GSER uses electrical idle inference to determine when a RX lane has reentered
09284                                                          electrical idle (EI). The PHY electrical idle exit detection supports a minimum pulse
09285                                                          width of 400 ps, therefore configurations that run faster than 2.5 G can indicate EI when
09286                                                          the serial lines are still driven. For rates faster than 2.5 G, it takes 16 K * 8 UI of
09287                                                          consecutive deasserted GSER()_RX_EIE_DETSTS[EIESTS] for the GSER to infer EI. In the
09288                                                          event of electrical idle inference, the following happens:
09289                                                          * GSER()_RX_EIE_DETSTS[CDRLOCK]<lane> is zeroed.
09290                                                          * GSER()_RX_EIE_DETSTS[EIELTCH]<lane> is zeroed.
09291                                                          * GSER()_RX_EIE_DETSTS[EIESTS]<lane> is zeroed.
09292                                                          * GSER()_RX_COAST[COAST]<lane> is asserted to prevent the CDR from trying to lock on
09293                                                          the incoming data stream.
09294                                                          * GSER()_RX_EIE_DETEN[EIEDE]<lane> deasserts for a short period of time, and then is
09295                                                          asserted to begin looking for the Electrical idle Exit condition.
09296                                                          Writing this register to a nonzero value causes the electrical idle inference to use the
09297                                                          [EII_FILT] count instead of the default settings. Each [EII_FILT] count represents 20 ns
09298                                                          of
09299                                                          incremental EI inference time.
09300                                                          It is not expected that software will need to use the Electrical Idle Inference logic. */
09301 #else
09302     uint64_t eii_filt                     : 16;
09303     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
09304 #endif
09305     } s;
09306     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter_s     cn73xx;
09307     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter_s     cn78xx;
09308     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter_s     cn78xxp1;
09309     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter_s     cnf75xx;
09310 };
09311 typedef union cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter cvmx_gserx_rx_eie_filter_t;

09503     uint64_t rx_tap1_hi_thrs              : 5;  /**< The high threshold for the local RX Tap1 count.
09504                                                          The far-end TX POST direction output, pcs_mac_rx_txpost_dir,
09505                                                          is set to increment if the local RX tap1 value from the VMA (after RX-EQ)
09506                                                          is higher than this value, and the local RX boost value is higher than
09507                                                          its high threshold GSER()_RX_TXDIR_CTRL_0[RX_BOOST_HI_THRS].
09508                                                          If GSER()_RX_TXDIR_CTRL_1[RX_TAP1_CHG_DIR]=1 then
09509                                                          the direction is decrement. */
09510     uint64_t rx_tap1_lo_thrs              : 5;  /**< The low threshold for the local RX Tap1 count.
09511                                                          The far-end TX POST direction output, pcs_mac_rx_txpost_dir,
09512                                                          is set to decrement if the local RX tap1 value from the VMA (after RX-EQ)
09513                                                          is lower than this value, and the local RX boost value is lower than
09514                                                          its low threshold GSER()_RX_TXDIR_CTRL_0[RX_BOOST_LO_THRS].
09515                                                          If GSER()_RX_TXDIR_CTRL_1[RX_TAP1_CHG_DIR]=1 then
09516                                                          the direction is increment. */
09517 #else
09518     uint64_t rx_tap1_lo_thrs              : 5;
09519     uint64_t rx_tap1_hi_thrs              : 5;
09520     uint64_t rx_tap1_chg_dir              : 1;
09521     uint64_t rx_precorr_chg_dir           : 1;
09522     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
09523 #endif
09524     } s;
09525     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_txdir_ctrl_1_s   cn73xx;
09526     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_txdir_ctrl_1_s   cn78xx;
09527     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_txdir_ctrl_1_s   cn78xxp1;
09528     struct cvmx_gserx_rx_txdir_ctrl_1_s   cnf75xx;
09529 };

10773 /**
10774  * cvmx_gser#_spd
10775  *
10776  * These registers are reset by hardware only during chip cold reset. The values of the CSR
10777  * fields in these registers do not change during chip warm or soft resets.
10778  */
10779 union cvmx_gserx_spd {
10780     uint64_t u64;
10781     struct cvmx_gserx_spd_s {
10782 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10783     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
10784     uint64_t spd                          : 4;  /**< For CCPI links (i.e. GSER8..13), the hardware loads this CSR field from the OCI_SPD<3:0>
10785                                                          pins during chip cold reset. For non-CCPI links, this field is not used.
10786                                                          For SPD settings that configure a non-default reference clock, hardware updates the PLL
10787                                                          settings of the specific lane mode (LMODE) table entry to derive the correct link rate.
10788                                                          <pre>
10789                                                                REFCLK  Link Rate
10790                                                          SPD   (MHz)   (Gb)      LMODE
10791                                                          ----  ------  ------    -----------------------
10792                                                          0x0:  100     1.25      R_125G_REFCLK15625_KX
10793                                                          0x1:  100     2.5       R_25G_REFCLK100
10794                                                          0x2:  100     5         R_5G_REFCLK100
10795                                                          0x3:  100     8         R_8G_REFCLK100
10796                                                          0x4:  125     1.25      R_125G_REFCLK15625_KX
10797                                                          0x5:  125     2.5       R_25G_REFCLK125
10798                                                          0x6:  125     3.125     R_3125G_REFCLK15625_XAUI
10799                                                          0x7:  125     5         R_5G_REFCLK125
10800                                                          0x8:  125     6.25      R_625G_REFCLK15625_RXAUI
10801                                                          0x9:  125     8         R_8G_REFCLK125
10802                                                          0xA:  156.25  2.5       R_25G_REFCLK100
10803                                                          0xB:  156.25  3.125     R_3125G_REFCLK15625_XAUI
10804                                                          0xC:  156.25  5         R_5G_REFCLK125
10805                                                          0xD:  156.25  6.25      R_625G_REFCLK15625_RXAUI
10806                                                          0xE:  156.25  10.3125   R_103125G_REFCLK15625_KR
10807                                                          0xF:                    SW_MODE
10808                                                          </pre>
10809                                                          Note that a value of 0xF is called SW_MODE. The CCPI link does not come up configured in
10810                                                          SW_MODE.
10811                                                          (Software must do all the CCPI GSER configuration to use CCPI in the case of SW_MODE.)
10812                                                          When SPD!=SW_MODE after a chip cold reset, the hardware has initialized the following
10813                                                          registers (based on the OCI_SPD selection):
10814                                                           * GSER()_LANE_MODE[LMODE]=Z.
10815                                                           * GSER()_PLL_P()_MODE_0.
10816                                                           * GSER()_PLL_P()_MODE_1.
10817                                                           * GSER()_LANE_P()_MODE_0.
10818                                                           * GSER()_LANE_P()_MODE_1.
10819                                                           * GSER()_LANE()_RX_VALBBD_CTRL_0.
10820                                                           * GSER()_LANE()_RX_VALBBD_CTRL_1.
10821                                                           * GSER()_LANE()_RX_VALBBD_CTRL_2.
10822                                                           where in "GSER(x)", x is 8..13, and in "P(z)", z equals LMODE. */
10823 #else
10824     uint64_t spd                          : 4;
10825     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
10826 #endif
10827     } s;
